{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"Jambo, bonjour, zdravstvujtye, dayo: these are a few of the languages"},{"time":9000,"text":"that I've spoken little bits of over the course of the last six weeks,"},{"time":13000,"text":"as I've been to 17 countries I think I'm up to, on this crazy tour I've been doing,"},{"time":18000,"text":"checking out various aspects of the project that we're doing."},{"time":21000,"text":"And I'm going to tell you a little bit about later on."},{"time":23000,"text":"And visiting some pretty incredible places,"},{"time":26000,"text":"places like Mongolia, Cambodia, New Guinea, South Africa, Tanzania twice --"},{"time":32000,"text":"I was here a month ago."}]},{"cues":[{"time":34000,"text":"And the opportunity to make a whirlwind tour of the world like that"},{"time":39000,"text":"is utterly amazing, for lots of reasons."},{"time":42000,"text":"You see some incredible stuff."},{"time":44000,"text":"And you get to make these spot comparisons"},{"time":46000,"text":"between people all around the globe."},{"time":48000,"text":"And the thing that you really take away from that,"},{"time":50000,"text":"the kind of surface thing that you take away from it,"},{"time":53000,"text":"is not that we're all one, although I'm going to tell you about that,"},{"time":57000,"text":"but rather how different we are."},{"time":59000,"text":"There is so much diversity around the globe."},{"time":62000,"text":"6,000 different languages spoken by six and a half billion people,"},{"time":65000,"text":"all different colors, shapes, sizes."},{"time":68000,"text":"You walk down the street in any big city, you travel like that,"},{"time":71000,"text":"and you are amazed at the diversity in the human species."}]},{"cues":[{"time":75000,"text":"How do we explain that diversity?"},{"time":78000,"text":"Well, that's what I'm going to talk about today,"},{"time":80000,"text":"is how we're using the tools of genetics,"},{"time":82000,"text":"population genetics in particular, to tell us how we generated this diversity,"},{"time":88000,"text":"and how long it took."},{"time":90000,"text":"Now, the problem of human diversity,"},{"time":92000,"text":"like all big scientific questions --"},{"time":94000,"text":"how do you explain something like that --"},{"time":96000,"text":"can be broken down into sub-questions."},{"time":98000,"text":"And you can ferret away at those little sub-questions."}]},{"cues":[{"time":101000,"text":"First one is really a question of origins."},{"time":103000,"text":"Do we all share a common origin, in fact?"},{"time":105000,"text":"And given that we do -- and that's the assumption"},{"time":108000,"text":"everybody, I think, in this room would make -- when was that?"},{"time":111000,"text":"When did we originate as a species?"},{"time":113000,"text":"How long have we been divergent from each other?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":115000,"text":"And the second question is related, but slightly different."},{"time":119000,"text":"If we do spring from a common source,"},{"time":121000,"text":"how did we come to occupy every corner of the globe,"},{"time":123000,"text":"and in the process generate all of this diversity,"},{"time":125000,"text":"the different ways of life, the different appearances,"},{"time":128000,"text":"the different languages around the world?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":130000,"text":"Well, the question of origins, as with so many other questions in biology,"},{"time":133000,"text":"seems to have been answered by Darwin over a century ago."},{"time":135000,"text":"In \"The Descent of Man,\" he wrote,"},{"time":137000,"text":"\"In each great region of the world, the living mammals"},{"time":139000,"text":"are closely related to the extinct species of the same region."},{"time":142000,"text":"It's therefore probable that Africa was formerly inhabited by extinct apes"},{"time":145000,"text":"closely allied to the gorilla and chimpanzee,"},{"time":148000,"text":"and as these two species are now man's nearest allies,"},{"time":151000,"text":"it's somewhat more probable that our early progenitors"},{"time":153000,"text":"lived on the African continent than elsewhere.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":155000,"text":"So we're done, we can go home -- finished the origin question."},{"time":159000,"text":"Well, not quite. Because Darwin was talking about our distant ancestry,"},{"time":163000,"text":"our common ancestry with apes."},{"time":165000,"text":"And it is quite clear that apes originated on the African continent."},{"time":169000,"text":"Around 23 million years ago, they appear in the fossil record."},{"time":172000,"text":"Africa was actually disconnected from the other landmasses at that time,"},{"time":175000,"text":"due to the vagaries of plate tectonics, floating around the Indian Ocean."},{"time":179000,"text":"Bumped into Eurasia around 16 million years ago,"},{"time":181000,"text":"and then we had the first African exodus, as we call it."},{"time":184000,"text":"The apes that left at that time ended up in Southeast Asia,"},{"time":186000,"text":"became the gibbons and the orangutans."},{"time":188000,"text":"And the ones that stayed on in Africa"},{"time":190000,"text":"evolved into the gorillas, the chimpanzees and us."},{"time":192000,"text":"So, yes, if you're talking about our common ancestry with apes,"},{"time":195000,"text":"it's very clear, by looking at the fossil record, we started off here."}]},{"cues":[{"time":199000,"text":"But that's not really the question I'm asking."},{"time":201000,"text":"I'm asking about our human ancestry,"},{"time":203000,"text":"things that we would recognize as being like us"},{"time":206000,"text":"if they were sitting here in the room."},{"time":208000,"text":"If they were peering over your shoulder,"},{"time":210000,"text":"you wouldn't leap back, like that. What about our human ancestry?"},{"time":213000,"text":"Because if we go far enough back,"},{"time":215000,"text":"we share a common ancestry with every living thing on Earth."},{"time":218000,"text":"DNA ties us all together, so we share ancestry with barracuda"},{"time":221000,"text":"and bacteria and mushrooms, if you go far enough back -- over a billion years."},{"time":226000,"text":"What we're asking about though is human ancestry."},{"time":228000,"text":"How do we study that?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":230000,"text":"Well, historically, it has been studied using the science of paleoanthropology."},{"time":234000,"text":"Digging things up out of the ground,"},{"time":236000,"text":"and largely on the basis of morphology --"},{"time":238000,"text":"the way things are shaped, often skull shape -- saying,"},{"time":241000,"text":"\"This looks a little bit more like us than that, so this must be my ancestor."},{"time":245000,"text":"This must be who I'm directly descended from.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":248000,"text":"The field of paleoanthropology, I'll argue,"},{"time":251000,"text":"gives us lots of fascinating possibilities about our ancestry,"},{"time":254000,"text":"but it doesn't give us the probabilities that we really want as scientists."},{"time":257000,"text":"What do I mean by that?"},{"time":259000,"text":"You're looking at a great example here."},{"time":261000,"text":"These are three extinct species of hominids,"},{"time":263000,"text":"potential human ancestors."},{"time":265000,"text":"All dug up just west of here in Olduvai Gorge, by the Leakey family."},{"time":268000,"text":"And they're all dating to roughly the same time."},{"time":270000,"text":"From left to right, we've got Homo erectus, Homo habilis,"},{"time":272000,"text":"and Australopithecus -- now called Paranthropus boisei,"},{"time":275000,"text":"the robust australopithecine. Three extinct species, same place, same time."},{"time":280000,"text":"That means that not all three could be my direct ancestor."},{"time":283000,"text":"Which one of these guys am I actually related to?"},{"time":286000,"text":"Possibilities about our ancestry, but not the probabilities that we're really looking for."}]},{"cues":[{"time":292000,"text":"Well, a different approach has been to look at morphology in humans"},{"time":296000,"text":"using the only data that people really had at hand until quite recently --"},{"time":299000,"text":"again, largely skull shape."},{"time":301000,"text":"The first person to do this systematically was Linnaeus,"},{"time":305000,"text":"Carl von Linne, a Swedish botanist,"},{"time":307000,"text":"who in the eighteenth century took it upon himself"},{"time":309000,"text":"to categorize every living organism on the planet."},{"time":311000,"text":"You think you've got a tough job?"},{"time":313000,"text":"And he did a pretty good job."},{"time":315000,"text":"He categorized about 12,000 species in \"Systema Naturae.\""},{"time":319000,"text":"He actually coined the term Homo sapiens -- it means wise man in Latin."},{"time":322000,"text":"But looking around the world at the diversity of humans, he said,"},{"time":326000,"text":"\"Well, you know, we seem to come in discreet sub-species or categories.\""},{"time":330000,"text":"And he talked about Africans and Americans and Asians and Europeans,"},{"time":334000,"text":"and a blatantly racist category he termed \"Monstrosus,\""},{"time":337000,"text":"which basically included all the people he didn't like,"},{"time":340000,"text":"including imaginary folk like elves."}]},{"cues":[{"time":344000,"text":"It's easy to dismiss this as the perhaps well-intentioned"},{"time":349000,"text":"but ultimately benighted musings of an eighteenth century scientist"},{"time":352000,"text":"working in the pre-Darwinian era."},{"time":354000,"text":"Except, if you had taken physical anthropology"},{"time":356000,"text":"as recently as 20 or 30 years ago, in many cases you would have learned"},{"time":360000,"text":"basically that same classification of humanity."},{"time":362000,"text":"Human races that according to physical anthropologists of 30, 40 years ago --"},{"time":367000,"text":"Carlton Coon is the best example --"},{"time":369000,"text":"had been diverging from each other -- this was in the post-Darwinian era --"},{"time":373000,"text":"for over a million years, since the time of Homo erectus."},{"time":376000,"text":"But based on what data?"},{"time":378000,"text":"Very little. Very little. Morphology and a lot of guesswork."}]},{"cues":[{"time":382000,"text":"Well, what I'm going to talk about today,"},{"time":384000,"text":"what I'm going to talk about now is a new approach to this problem."},{"time":387000,"text":"Instead of going out and guessing about our ancestry,"},{"time":390000,"text":"digging things up out of the ground, possible ancestors,"},{"time":392000,"text":"and saying it on the basis of morphology --"},{"time":394000,"text":"which we still don't completely understand,"},{"time":396000,"text":"we don't know the genetic causes underlying this morphological variation --"}]},{"cues":[{"time":400000,"text":"what we need to do is turn the problem on its head."},{"time":402000,"text":"Because what we're really asking is a genealogical problem,"},{"time":406000,"text":"or a genealogical question."},{"time":408000,"text":"What we're trying to do is construct a family tree for everybody alive today."},{"time":413000,"text":"And as any genealogist will tell you --"},{"time":415000,"text":"anybody have a member of the family, or maybe you"},{"time":417000,"text":"have tried to construct a family tree, trace back in time?"},{"time":420000,"text":"You start in the present, with relationships you're certain about."},{"time":422000,"text":"You and your siblings, you have a parent in common."},{"time":424000,"text":"You and your cousins share a grandparent in common."},{"time":426000,"text":"You gradually trace further and further back into the past,"},{"time":429000,"text":"adding these ever more distant relationships."},{"time":431000,"text":"But eventually, no matter how good you are at digging up the church records,"},{"time":435000,"text":"and all that stuff, you hit what the genealogists call a brick wall."},{"time":439000,"text":"A point beyond which you don't know anything else about your ancestors,"},{"time":442000,"text":"and you enter this dark and mysterious realm we call history"},{"time":446000,"text":"that we have to feel our way through with whispered guidance."}]},{"cues":[{"time":449000,"text":"Who were these people who came before?"},{"time":451000,"text":"We have no written record. Well, actually, we do."},{"time":454000,"text":"Written in our DNA, in our genetic code --"},{"time":457000,"text":"we have a historical document that takes us back in time"},{"time":459000,"text":"to the very earliest days of our species. And that's what we study."}]},{"cues":[{"time":463000,"text":"Now, a quick primer on DNA."},{"time":465000,"text":"I suspect that not everybody in the audience is a geneticist."},{"time":468000,"text":"It is a very long, linear molecule, a coded version"},{"time":472000,"text":"of how to make another copy of you. It's your blueprint."},{"time":475000,"text":"It's composed of four subunits: A, C, G and T, we call them."},{"time":478000,"text":"And it's the sequence of those subunits that defines that blueprint."},{"time":482000,"text":"How long is it? Well, it's billions of these subunits in length."},{"time":485000,"text":"A haploid genome -- we actually have two copies of all of our chromosomes --"},{"time":488000,"text":"a haploid genome is around 3.2 billion nucleotides in length."},{"time":492000,"text":"And the whole thing, if you add it all together,"},{"time":494000,"text":"is over six billion nucleotides long."},{"time":496000,"text":"If you take all the DNA out of one cell in your body,"},{"time":499000,"text":"and stretch it end to end, it's around two meters long."},{"time":503000,"text":"If you take all the DNA out of every cell in your body,"},{"time":505000,"text":"and you stretch it end to end, it would reach from here to the moon and back,"},{"time":509000,"text":"thousands of times. It's a lot of information."}]},{"cues":[{"time":512000,"text":"And so when you're copying this DNA molecule to pass it on, it's a pretty tough job."},{"time":518000,"text":"Imagine the longest book you can think of, \"War and Peace.\""},{"time":522000,"text":"Now multiply it by 100."},{"time":524000,"text":"And imagine copying that by hand."},{"time":526000,"text":"And you're working away until late at night,"},{"time":528000,"text":"and you're very, very careful, and you're drinking coffee"},{"time":530000,"text":"and you're paying attention, but, occasionally,"},{"time":532000,"text":"when you're copying this by hand,"},{"time":534000,"text":"you're going to make a little typo, a spelling mistake --"},{"time":536000,"text":"substitute an I for an E, or a C for a T."}]},{"cues":[{"time":540000,"text":"Same thing happens to our DNA as it's being passed on through the generations."},{"time":544000,"text":"It doesn't happen very often. We have a proofreading mechanism built in."},{"time":547000,"text":"But when it does happen, and these changes get transmitted down"},{"time":549000,"text":"through the generations, they become markers of descent."},{"time":552000,"text":"If you share a marker with someone,"},{"time":554000,"text":"it means you share an ancestor at some point in the past,"},{"time":557000,"text":"the person who first had that change in their DNA."},{"time":559000,"text":"And it's by looking at the pattern of genetic variation,"},{"time":562000,"text":"the pattern of these markers in people all over the world,"},{"time":565000,"text":"and assessing the relative ages when they occurred throughout our history,"},{"time":569000,"text":"that we've been able to construct a family tree for everybody alive today."}]},{"cues":[{"time":572000,"text":"These are two pieces of DNA that we use quite widely in our work."},{"time":575000,"text":"Mitochondrial DNA, tracing a purely maternal line of descent."},{"time":578000,"text":"You get your mtDNA from your mother, and your mother's mother,"},{"time":581000,"text":"all the way back to the very first woman."},{"time":583000,"text":"The Y chromosome, the piece of DNA that makes men men,"},{"time":586000,"text":"traces a purely paternal line of descent."},{"time":589000,"text":"Everybody in this room, everybody in the world,"},{"time":593000,"text":"falls into a lineage somewhere on these trees."},{"time":597000,"text":"Now, even though these are simplified versions of the real trees,"},{"time":600000,"text":"they're still kind of complicated, so let's simplify them."},{"time":602000,"text":"Turn them on their sides, combine them so that they look like a tree"},{"time":604000,"text":"with the root at the bottom and the branches going up."},{"time":607000,"text":"What's the take-home message?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":609000,"text":"Well, the thing that jumps out at you first"},{"time":611000,"text":"is that the deepest lineages in our family trees"},{"time":614000,"text":"are found within Africa, among Africans."},{"time":619000,"text":"That means that Africans have been accumulating"},{"time":622000,"text":"this mutational diversity for longer."},{"time":625000,"text":"And what that means is that we originated in Africa. It's written in our DNA."},{"time":629000,"text":"Every piece of DNA we look at has greater diversity within Africa than outside of Africa."},{"time":634000,"text":"And at some point in the past, a sub-group of Africans"},{"time":637000,"text":"left the African continent to go out and populate the rest of the world."}]},{"cues":[{"time":641000,"text":"Now, how recently do we share this ancestry?"},{"time":643000,"text":"Was it millions of years ago, which we might suspect"},{"time":647000,"text":"by looking at all this incredible variation around the world?"},{"time":650000,"text":"No, the DNA tells a story that's very clear."},{"time":653000,"text":"Within the last 200,000 years, we all share an ancestor, a single person --"},{"time":658000,"text":"Mitochondrial Eve, you might have heard about her -- in Africa,"},{"time":662000,"text":"an African woman who gave rise to all the mitochondrial diversity in the world today."}]},{"cues":[{"time":665000,"text":"But what's even more amazing"},{"time":667000,"text":"is that if you look at the Y-chromosome side,"},{"time":669000,"text":"the male side of the story, the Y-chromosome Adam"},{"time":673000,"text":"only lived around 60,000 years ago."},{"time":675000,"text":"That's only about 2,000 human generations,"},{"time":678000,"text":"the blink of an eye in an evolutionary sense."},{"time":682000,"text":"That tells us we were all still living in Africa at that time."},{"time":685000,"text":"This was an African man who gave rise"},{"time":687000,"text":"to all the Y chromosome diversity around the world."},{"time":689000,"text":"It's only within the last 60,000 years"},{"time":691000,"text":"that we have started to generate this incredible diversity we see around the world."},{"time":695000,"text":"Such an amazing story."},{"time":697000,"text":"We're all effectively part of an extended African family."}]},{"cues":[{"time":701000,"text":"Now, that seems so recent. Why didn't we start to leave earlier?"},{"time":704000,"text":"Why didn't Homo erectus evolve into separate species,"},{"time":708000,"text":"or sub-species rather, human races around the world?"},{"time":710000,"text":"Why was it that we seem to have come out of Africa so recently?"},{"time":714000,"text":"Well, that's a big question. These \"why\" questions,"},{"time":716000,"text":"particularly in genetics and the study of history in general, are always the big ones,"},{"time":721000,"text":"the ones that are tough to answer."}]},{"cues":[{"time":723000,"text":"And so when all else fails, talk about the weather."},{"time":726000,"text":"What was going on to the world's weather around 60,000 years ago?"},{"time":729000,"text":"Well, we were going into the worst part of the last ice age."},{"time":732000,"text":"The last ice age started roughly 120,000 years ago."},{"time":735000,"text":"It went up and down, and it really started to accelerate around 70,000 years ago."},{"time":739000,"text":"Lots of evidence from sediment cores"},{"time":741000,"text":"and the pollen types, oxygen isotopes and so on."},{"time":744000,"text":"We hit the last glacial maximum around 16,000 years ago,"},{"time":747000,"text":"but basically, from 70,000 years on, things were getting really tough,"},{"time":751000,"text":"getting very cold. The Northern Hemisphere had massive growing ice sheets."},{"time":756000,"text":"New York City, Chicago, Seattle, all under a sheet of ice."},{"time":760000,"text":"Most of Britain, all of Scandinavia, covered by ice several kilometers thick."}]},{"cues":[{"time":765000,"text":"Now, Africa is the most tropical continent on the planet --"},{"time":768000,"text":"about 85 percent of it lies between Cancer and Capricorn --"},{"time":772000,"text":"and there aren't a lot of glaciers here,"},{"time":774000,"text":"except on the high mountains here in East Africa."},{"time":776000,"text":"So what was going on here? We weren't covered in ice in Africa."},{"time":779000,"text":"Rather, Africa was drying out at that time."},{"time":782000,"text":"This is a paleo-climatological map"},{"time":784000,"text":"of what Africa looked like between 60,000 and 70,000 years ago,"},{"time":787000,"text":"reconstructed from all these pieces of evidence that I mentioned before."},{"time":791000,"text":"The reason for that is that ice actually sucks moisture out of the atmosphere."},{"time":795000,"text":"If you think about Antarctica, it's technically a desert, it gets so little precipitation."}]},{"cues":[{"time":799000,"text":"So the whole world was drying out."},{"time":801000,"text":"The sea levels were dropping. And Africa was turning to desert."},{"time":805000,"text":"The Sahara was much bigger then than it is now."},{"time":808000,"text":"And the human habitat was reduced to just a few small pockets,"},{"time":811000,"text":"compared to what we have today."},{"time":813000,"text":"The evidence from genetic data"},{"time":815000,"text":"is that the human population around this time, roughly 70,000 years ago,"},{"time":818000,"text":"crashed to fewer than 2,000 individuals."},{"time":821000,"text":"We nearly went extinct. We were hanging on by our fingernails."}]},{"cues":[{"time":825000,"text":"And then something happened. A great illustration of it."},{"time":828000,"text":"Look at some stone tools."},{"time":830000,"text":"The ones on the left are from Africa, from around a million years ago."},{"time":834000,"text":"The ones on the right were made by Neanderthals, our distant cousins,"},{"time":837000,"text":"not our direct ancestors, living in Europe,"},{"time":839000,"text":"and they date from around 50,000 or 60,000 years ago."},{"time":843000,"text":"Now, at the risk of offending any paleoanthropologists"},{"time":846000,"text":"or physical anthropologists in the audience,"},{"time":849000,"text":"basically there's not a lot of change between these two stone tool groups."},{"time":854000,"text":"The ones on the left are pretty similar to the ones on the right."},{"time":857000,"text":"We are in a period of long cultural stasis from a million years ago"},{"time":861000,"text":"until around 60,000 to 70,000 years ago."},{"time":863000,"text":"The tool styles don't change that much."},{"time":865000,"text":"The evidence is that the human way of life"},{"time":867000,"text":"didn't change that much during that period."}]},{"cues":[{"time":869000,"text":"But then 50, 60, 70 thousand years ago, somewhere in that region,"},{"time":874000,"text":"all hell breaks loose. Art makes its appearance."},{"time":877000,"text":"The stone tools become much more finely crafted."},{"time":880000,"text":"The evidence is that humans begin to specialize in particular prey species,"},{"time":883000,"text":"at particular times of the year."},{"time":885000,"text":"The population size started to expand."},{"time":888000,"text":"Probably, according to what many linguists believe,"},{"time":890000,"text":"fully modern language, syntactic language -- subject, verb, object --"},{"time":894000,"text":"that we use to convey complex ideas, like I'm doing now, appeared around that time."},{"time":898000,"text":"We became much more social. The social networks expanded."}]},{"cues":[{"time":902000,"text":"This change in behavior allowed us to survive these worsening conditions in Africa,"},{"time":907000,"text":"and they allowed us to start to expand around the world."},{"time":912000,"text":"We've been talking at this conference about African success stories."},{"time":915000,"text":"Well, you want the ultimate African success story?"},{"time":918000,"text":"Look in the mirror. You're it. The reason you're alive today"},{"time":921000,"text":"is because of those changes in our brains that took place in Africa --"},{"time":925000,"text":"probably somewhere in the region where we're sitting right now,"},{"time":928000,"text":"around 60, 70 thousand years ago --"},{"time":931000,"text":"allowing us not only to survive in Africa, but to expand out of Africa."},{"time":934000,"text":"An early coastal migration along the south coast of Asia,"},{"time":937000,"text":"leaving Africa around 60,000 years ago,"},{"time":939000,"text":"reaching Australia very rapidly, by 50,000 years ago."},{"time":943000,"text":"A slightly later migration up into the Middle East."},{"time":945000,"text":"These would have been savannah hunters."}]},{"cues":[{"time":947000,"text":"So those of you who are going on one of the post-conference tours,"},{"time":949000,"text":"you'll get to see what a real savannah is like."},{"time":951000,"text":"And it's basically a meat locker."},{"time":953000,"text":"People who would have specialized in killing the animals,"},{"time":956000,"text":"hunting the animals on those meat locker savannahs, moving up,"},{"time":959000,"text":"following the grasslands into the Middle East around 45,000 years ago,"},{"time":963000,"text":"during one of the rare wet phases in the Sahara."},{"time":965000,"text":"Migrating eastward, following the grasslands,"},{"time":968000,"text":"because that's what they were adapted to live on."}]},{"cues":[{"time":970000,"text":"And when they reached Central Asia,"},{"time":972000,"text":"they reached what was effectively a steppe super-highway,"},{"time":975000,"text":"a grassland super-highway."},{"time":977000,"text":"The grasslands at that time -- this was during the last ice age --"},{"time":979000,"text":"stretched basically from Germany all the way over to Korea,"},{"time":982000,"text":"and the entire continent was open to them."},{"time":984000,"text":"Entering Europe around 35,000 years ago,"},{"time":986000,"text":"and finally, a small group migrating up"},{"time":988000,"text":"through the worst weather imaginable, Siberia,"},{"time":992000,"text":"inside the Arctic Circle, during the last ice age --"},{"time":994000,"text":"temperature was at -70, -80, even -100, perhaps --"},{"time":998000,"text":"migrating into the Americas, ultimately reaching that final frontier."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1002000,"text":"An amazing story, and it happened first in Africa."},{"time":1006000,"text":"The changes that allowed us to do that,"},{"time":1008000,"text":"the evolution of this highly adaptable brain that we all carry around with us,"},{"time":1011000,"text":"allowing us to create novel cultures,"},{"time":1013000,"text":"allowing us to develop the diversity"},{"time":1016000,"text":"that we see on a whirlwind trip like the one I've just been on."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1020000,"text":"Now, that story I just told you is literally a whirlwind tour"},{"time":1024000,"text":"of how we populated the world, the great Paleolithic wanderings of our species."},{"time":1029000,"text":"And that's the story that I told a couple of years ago"},{"time":1031000,"text":"in my book, \"The Journey of Man,\" and a film that we made with the same title."},{"time":1035000,"text":"And as we were finishing up that film --"},{"time":1038000,"text":"it was co-produced with National Geographic --"},{"time":1040000,"text":"I started talking to the folks at NG about this work."},{"time":1043000,"text":"And they got really excited about it. They liked the film, but they said,"},{"time":1047000,"text":"\"You know, we really see this as kind of"},{"time":1049000,"text":"the next wave in the study of human origins, where we all came from,"},{"time":1053000,"text":"using the tools of DNA to map the migrations around the world."},{"time":1058000,"text":"You know, the study of human origins is kind of in our DNA,"},{"time":1060000,"text":"and we want to take it to the next level."},{"time":1062000,"text":"What do you want to do next?\""},{"time":1064000,"text":"Which is a great question to be asked by National Geographic."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1066000,"text":"And I said, \"Well, you know, what I've sketched out here is just that."},{"time":1070000,"text":"It is a very coarse sketch of how we migrated around the planet."},{"time":1074000,"text":"And it's based on a few thousand people we've sampled from,"},{"time":1077000,"text":"you know, a handful of populations around the world."},{"time":1079000,"text":"Studied a few genetic markers, and there are lots of gaps on this map."},{"time":1083000,"text":"We've just connected the dots. What we need to do"},{"time":1085000,"text":"is increase our sample size by an order of magnitude or more --"},{"time":1089000,"text":"hundreds of thousands of DNA samples from people all over the world.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":1093000,"text":"And that was the genesis of the Genographic Project."},{"time":1096000,"text":"The project launched in April 2005."},{"time":1099000,"text":"It has three core components. Obviously, science is a big part of it."},{"time":1103000,"text":"The field research that we're doing around the world with indigenous peoples."},{"time":1106000,"text":"People who have lived in the same location for a long period of time"},{"time":1109000,"text":"retain a connection to the place where they live"},{"time":1111000,"text":"that many of the rest of us have lost."},{"time":1114000,"text":"So my ancestors come from all over northern Europe."},{"time":1116000,"text":"I live in the Eastern Seaboard of North America when I'm not traveling."},{"time":1119000,"text":"Where am I indigenous to? Nowhere really. My genes are all jumbled up."},{"time":1122000,"text":"But there are people who retain that link to their ancestors"},{"time":1125000,"text":"that allows us to contextualize the DNA results."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1128000,"text":"That's the focus of the field research,"},{"time":1130000,"text":"the centers that we've set up all over the world --"},{"time":1132000,"text":"10 of them, top population geneticists."},{"time":1135000,"text":"But, in addition, we wanted to open up this study to anybody around the world."},{"time":1138000,"text":"How often do you get to participate in a big scientific project?"},{"time":1142000,"text":"The Human Genome Project, or a Mars Rover mission."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1144000,"text":"In this case, you actually can."},{"time":1146000,"text":"You can go onto our website, Nationalgeographic.com/genographic."},{"time":1150000,"text":"You can order a kit. You can test your own DNA."},{"time":1153000,"text":"And you can actually submit those results to the database,"},{"time":1156000,"text":"and tell us a little about your genealogical background,"},{"time":1158000,"text":"have the data analyzed as part of the scientific effort."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1162000,"text":"Now, this is all a nonprofit enterprise, and so the money that we raise,"},{"time":1166000,"text":"after we cover the cost of doing the testing and making the kit components,"},{"time":1169000,"text":"gets plowed back into the project."},{"time":1171000,"text":"The majority going to something we call the Legacy Fund."},{"time":1173000,"text":"It's a charitable entity, basically a grant-giving entity"},{"time":1177000,"text":"that gives money back to indigenous groups around the world"},{"time":1179000,"text":"for educational, cultural projects initiated by them."},{"time":1183000,"text":"They apply to this fund in order to do various projects,"},{"time":1185000,"text":"and I'll show you a couple of examples."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1187000,"text":"So how are we doing on the project? We've got about 25,000 samples"},{"time":1190000,"text":"collected from indigenous people around the world."},{"time":1192000,"text":"The most amazing thing has been the interest on the part of the public;"},{"time":1195000,"text":"210,000 people have ordered these participation kits"},{"time":1198000,"text":"since we launched two years ago,"},{"time":1200000,"text":"which has raised around five million dollars,"},{"time":1203000,"text":"the majority of which, at least half, is going back into the Legacy Fund."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1206000,"text":"We've just awarded the first Legacy Grants totaling around 500,000 dollars."},{"time":1210000,"text":"Projects around the world -- documenting oral poetry in Sierra Leone,"},{"time":1213000,"text":"preserving traditional weaving patterns in Gaza,"},{"time":1216000,"text":"language revitalization in Tajikistan, etc., etc."},{"time":1219000,"text":"So the project is going very, very well,"},{"time":1222000,"text":"and I urge you to check out the website and watch this space."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1226000,"text":"Thank you very much."},{"time":1228000,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}